export const GENERATED_QUESTIONS_3: SeedQuestion[] = [
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Explain the Relationship Between Variables","difficulty":1,"stem":"A researcher records how a plant's height changes based on the number of days since it was planted. In this study, which is the independent variable?","options":["The plant's height","Number of days since planting","The type of soil used","The amount of water given"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The independent variable is the one that is changed or that drives the change; the dependent variable responds to it. Here height depends on time, so the number of days is the independent variable and the plant's height is the dependent variable.","rationale":{"takeaway":"The independent variable is the input that drives the change; the dependent variable is the outcome that responds to it.","steps":["Ask which quantity changes on its own: time passes regardless of the plant, so days since planting is the input.","Ask which quantity responds: the plant's height changes as the days accumulate, so height is the outcome."],"whyCorrect":"The study records height based on the number of days, so days is the variable the height depends on.","distractors":{"0":"The plant's height is the dependent variable, the outcome being measured as time passes.","2":"The type of soil is held constant in this study; it is a controlled condition, not the variable being tracked.","3":"The amount of water is not part of the stated relationship; it would be a controlled variable, not the driver."},"commonMistake":"Picking the quantity being measured (height) because it is what gets recorded. The recorded outcome is the dependent variable, not the independent one."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Explain the Relationship Between Variables","difficulty":2,"stem":"A store tracks its monthly profit based on the amount of money it spends on advertising each month. Which variable is the dependent variable?","options":["Monthly profit","The month of the year","Advertising spending","The number of employees"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The dependent variable is the outcome being measured, which depends on another variable. Profit depends on advertising spending, so profit is the dependent variable and advertising spending is the independent variable.","rationale":{"takeaway":"The dependent variable is the measured outcome that depends on another quantity.","steps":["Identify the input the store controls: advertising spending.","Identify the outcome that responds to that input: monthly profit."],"whyCorrect":"Profit is tracked based on advertising spending, so profit is the outcome that depends on the other variable.","distractors":{"1":"The month of the year is just a label for when each data point was collected, not a variable in the stated relationship.","2":"Advertising spending is the independent variable, the input the store chooses.","3":"The number of employees is not part of the relationship being studied; it is an outside factor."},"commonMistake":"Reversing the roles: the quantity a business controls (spending) is the independent variable, and the result it watches (profit) is the dependent one."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Explain the Relationship Between Variables","difficulty":2,"stem":"For a fixed driving distance, as a car's speed increases, the time needed to complete the trip decreases. What type of relationship does this describe between speed and time?","options":["No relationship","Equal relationship","Inverse relationship","Direct relationship"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"In a direct relationship both quantities increase together; in an inverse relationship one increases while the other decreases. Since higher speed leads to lower time, this is an inverse relationship.","rationale":{"takeaway":"When one quantity rises while the other falls, the relationship is inverse; when both rise together, it is direct.","steps":["For a fixed distance, distance = speed × time, so speed and time multiply to a constant.","If speed goes up, time must come down to keep the product the same. One up, one down is the inverse pattern."],"whyCorrect":"Doubling the speed halves the trip time, the defining behavior of an inverse relationship.","distractors":{"0":"There clearly is a relationship: changing the speed changes the time needed.","1":"Equal relationship is not a standard relationship type, and speed and time are not equal quantities.","3":"A direct relationship means both quantities increase together; here time decreases as speed increases."},"commonMistake":"Calling any strong connection a direct relationship. Direction matters: opposite movement means inverse."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Explain the Relationship Between Variables","difficulty":1,"stem":"At a constant price per pound, the total cost of apples increases as the number of pounds purchased increases. This is an example of what kind of relationship?","options":["Negative relationship","Direct relationship","Inverse relationship","No relationship"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"When two quantities increase together, they have a direct relationship. As pounds purchased go up, total cost goes up, so cost and weight have a direct relationship.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Two quantities that increase together have a direct relationship.","steps":["Total cost = price per pound × pounds, with the price fixed.","Buying more pounds raises the total cost, so both quantities move in the same direction."],"whyCorrect":"More pounds always means more cost at a constant price, so cost varies directly with weight.","distractors":{"0":"A negative relationship means one quantity falls as the other rises; here both rise together.","2":"An inverse relationship also means opposite movement, which does not happen here.","3":"Cost clearly depends on pounds purchased, so there is a relationship."},"commonMistake":"Confusing direct with inverse. Same direction means direct; opposite directions mean inverse."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Evaluate Information in Tables, Charts, and Graphs Using Statistics","difficulty":1,"stem":"The frequency table below shows the number of pets owned by households surveyed.\nPets | Households\n0 | 5\n1 | 8\n2 | 3\n3 | 1\nWhat is the mode of the number of pets owned?","options":["2","8","0","1"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The mode is the data value that occurs most often, which is the value with the highest frequency. The frequency 8 is the largest, and it belongs to the value 1 pet, so the mode is 1. (8 is the frequency, not the data value.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"The mode is the data value with the highest frequency, not the frequency itself.","steps":["Scan the frequency column: 5, 8, 3, 1. The largest is 8.","Read across to the value that frequency belongs to: 8 households own 1 pet, so the mode is 1."],"whyCorrect":"More households (8) reported 1 pet than any other count, so 1 is the most common number of pets.","distractors":{"0":"Only 3 households own 2 pets, which is not the highest frequency.","1":"8 is the frequency (how many households), not a number of pets; the mode must be a data value.","2":"5 households own 0 pets, fewer than the 8 who own 1."},"commonMistake":"Reporting the largest frequency (8) instead of the value it belongs to (1 pet)."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Evaluate Information in Tables, Charts, and Graphs Using Statistics","difficulty":3,"stem":"The frequency table below shows quiz scores for a class of 10 students.\nScore | Frequency\n70 | 2\n80 | 3\n90 | 4\n100 | 1\nWhat is the median score?","options":["87.5","80","90","85"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Listing the 10 scores in order: 70, 70, 80, 80, 80, 90, 90, 90, 90, 100. With 10 values the median is the average of the 5th and 6th values, which are 80 and 90. The median is (80 + 90) / 2 = 85.","rationale":{"takeaway":"To find a median from a frequency table, expand every value by its frequency, then average the two middle values when the count is even.","steps":["Expand the table into the full list: 70, 70, 80, 80, 80, 90, 90, 90, 90, 100.","With 10 values, the median is the average of the 5th and 6th values: 80 and 90.","Compute (80 + 90) / 2 = 85."],"whyCorrect":"Exactly five scores sit at or below 85 and five sit at or above it, which is what the median requires.","distractors":{"0":"87.5 comes from averaging the wrong pair of middle values after mis-listing the data; the true 5th and 6th values are 80 and 90.","1":"80 is only the 5th value; with an even count you must average the 5th and 6th values, not stop at one of them.","2":"90 is the 6th value and also the mode; picking the most frequent score is not the same as finding the middle."},"commonMistake":"Taking the median of the four listed score values (70, 80, 90, 100) without expanding each one by its frequency."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Evaluate Information in Tables, Charts, and Graphs Using Statistics","difficulty":2,"stem":"The frequency table below shows goals scored by a team across 10 games.\nGoals | Games\n0 | 2\n1 | 4\n2 | 3\n3 | 1\nWhat is the mean number of goals per game?","options":["1.5","1.3","13","2"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Multiply each value by its frequency and add: (0)(2) + (1)(4) + (2)(3) + (3)(1) = 0 + 4 + 6 + 3 = 13 total goals. Divide by the total of 10 games: 13 / 10 = 1.3. (13 is the total, not the mean.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"A mean from a frequency table is the weighted total (value × frequency summed) divided by the total frequency.","steps":["Multiply each goal count by its number of games: (0)(2) + (1)(4) + (2)(3) + (3)(1).","Add the products: 0 + 4 + 6 + 3 = 13 total goals.","Divide by the total games: 13 ÷ 10 = 1.3."],"whyCorrect":"Estimate check: most games had 1 or 2 goals, so a mean a little over 1 is sensible; 1.3 fits.","distractors":{"0":"1.5 is the mean of just the values 0, 1, 2, 3 (6 ÷ 4), ignoring how often each occurred.","2":"13 is the total number of goals; it still needs to be divided by the 10 games.","3":"2 comes from averaging only the nonzero values (1 + 2 + 3) ÷ 3, dropping the games with 0 goals."},"commonMistake":"Averaging the value column alone. Each value must be weighted by its frequency before dividing."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Evaluate Information in Tables, Charts, and Graphs Using Statistics","difficulty":2,"stem":"The frequency table below shows a set of data values and how often each occurs.\nValue | Frequency\n1 | 1\n2 | 2\n3 | 3\n4 | 4\nWhat is the mean of the data set?","options":["2.5","10","3","3.5"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Multiply each value by its frequency and add: (1)(1) + (2)(2) + (3)(3) + (4)(4) = 1 + 4 + 9 + 16 = 30. The total number of data values is 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 = 10. The mean is 30 / 10 = 3. (2.5 is the average of just the four values 1, 2, 3, 4.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Weight each value by its frequency, total everything, then divide by the number of data points (the frequency total).","steps":["Multiply value by frequency: (1)(1) + (2)(2) + (3)(3) + (4)(4) = 1 + 4 + 9 + 16 = 30.","Count the data points: 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 = 10.","Divide: 30 ÷ 10 = 3."],"whyCorrect":"The data leans toward the higher values (3 and 4 occur most), so a mean of 3, above the midpoint 2.5, is consistent.","distractors":{"0":"2.5 is the average of just the four listed values (1 + 2 + 3 + 4) ÷ 4, ignoring the frequencies.","1":"10 is the number of data points (the frequency total), not the mean.","3":"3.5 comes from averaging the two most frequent values, 3 and 4, instead of computing the weighted mean."},"commonMistake":"Dividing by the number of rows (4) or ignoring frequencies entirely instead of dividing the weighted total by 10."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"An L-shaped figure is formed by starting with a rectangle 8 cm wide and 10 cm tall, then removing a 3 cm by 4 cm rectangular piece from one corner. What is the area of the remaining L-shaped figure? (Area of a rectangle = length × width.)","options":["56 cm²","92 cm²","68 cm²","80 cm²"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Find the full rectangle's area: 8 × 10 = 80 cm². Find the removed piece: 3 × 4 = 12 cm². Subtract: 80 − 12 = 68 cm². (80 forgets to remove the piece; 92 incorrectly adds it.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"The area of an L-shape is the full rectangle's area minus the removed corner piece.","steps":["Full rectangle: 8 × 10 = 80 cm².","Removed piece: 3 × 4 = 12 cm².","Subtract: 80 − 12 = 68 cm²."],"whyCorrect":"The remaining figure must be smaller than the original 80 cm² but only by the small 12 cm² notch, and 68 cm² fits that.","distractors":{"0":"56 cm² subtracts the 12 cm² piece twice (80 − 12 − 12).","1":"92 cm² adds the removed piece (80 + 12) instead of subtracting it.","3":"80 cm² is the full rectangle's area, forgetting to remove the corner piece."},"commonMistake":"Stopping at the full rectangle's area. A removed piece must be subtracted, never added."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":3,"stem":"A composite figure consists of a rectangle 10 cm long and 6 cm wide with a semicircle attached to one of the 6 cm ends. The semicircle's diameter equals 6 cm. Using π ≈ 3.14, what is the total area of the figure? (Area of a circle = πr².)","options":["60 cm²","74.13 cm²","116.52 cm²","88.26 cm²"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Rectangle area = 10 × 6 = 60 cm². The semicircle has radius r = 6 / 2 = 3 cm, so its area = (1/2)πr² = (1/2)(3.14)(3²) = (1/2)(3.14)(9) = 14.13 cm². Total = 60 + 14.13 = 74.13 cm². (88.26 uses a full circle; 116.52 uses the diameter 6 as the radius; 60 forgets the semicircle.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"For composite figures, find each simple shape's area separately and add them, halving a circle's area for a semicircle.","steps":["Rectangle: 10 × 6 = 60 cm².","Radius of the semicircle: 6 ÷ 2 = 3 cm.","Semicircle: (1/2)πr² = (1/2)(3.14)(9) = 14.13 cm².","Total: 60 + 14.13 = 74.13 cm²."],"whyCorrect":"The semicircle is small compared with the rectangle, so a total just above 60 cm² is the right size; 74.13 cm² fits.","distractors":{"0":"60 cm² is the rectangle alone, leaving out the semicircle.","2":"116.52 cm² uses the diameter 6 as the radius, computing (1/2)(3.14)(36) = 56.52 for the semicircle.","3":"88.26 cm² adds a full circle (3.14 × 9 = 28.26) instead of half of one."},"commonMistake":"Using the diameter in πr². Halve the diameter first: r = 6 ÷ 2 = 3."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"An L-shaped garden has six straight sides. Going around the edge, the side lengths in order are 6 m, 2 m, 3 m, 3 m, 3 m, and 5 m. What is the perimeter of the garden?","options":["21 m","20 m","24 m","22 m"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Perimeter is the total distance around the figure, so add all six side lengths: 6 + 2 + 3 + 3 + 3 + 5 = 22 m. (21 m is the area of this figure, not its perimeter.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Perimeter is the sum of every side length around the outside of the figure.","steps":["List all six sides: 6, 2, 3, 3, 3, 5.","Add them: 6 + 2 + 3 + 3 + 3 + 5 = 22 m."],"whyCorrect":"Check by grouping: horizontal edges give 6 = 3 + 3 and vertical edges give 5 = 2 + 3, so the sides close up correctly and total 22 m.","distractors":{"0":"21 m is the area of this figure (6 × 5 − 3 × 3), not the distance around it.","1":"20 m drops one of the sides, such as the 2 m edge, from the sum.","2":"24 m comes from an addition slip, such as counting one of the sides twice."},"commonMistake":"Mixing up perimeter with area. Perimeter adds edge lengths; area multiplies dimensions."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"A closed rectangular box has length 5 cm, width 3 cm, and height 4 cm. What is its total surface area? (box SA = 2(lw + lh + wh).)","options":["70 cm²","47 cm²","60 cm²","94 cm²"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Apply box SA = 2(lw + lh + wh) = 2((5)(3) + (5)(4) + (3)(4)) = 2(15 + 20 + 12) = 2(47) = 94 cm². (47 forgets to multiply by 2; 60 is the volume 5 × 3 × 4.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"A closed box has three pairs of matching faces, so its surface area is 2(lw + lh + wh).","steps":["Face areas: lw = (5)(3) = 15, lh = (5)(4) = 20, wh = (3)(4) = 12.","Add them: 15 + 20 + 12 = 47.","Double for the matching opposite faces: 2 × 47 = 94 cm²."],"whyCorrect":"All six faces are counted: two 15s, two 20s, and two 12s sum to 94 cm².","distractors":{"0":"70 cm² doubles only the 15 and 20 faces, leaving out the two 3 × 4 = 12 faces.","1":"47 cm² is the sum of the three distinct faces without doubling; a box has six faces, not three.","2":"60 cm² is the volume 5 × 3 × 4, not the surface area."},"commonMistake":"Forgetting the factor of 2. Each face has an identical opposite face, so the three products must be doubled."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"A closed rectangular carton measures 8 in by 4 in by 2 in. What is its total surface area? (box SA = 2(lw + lh + wh).)","options":["112 in²","100 in²","56 in²","64 in²"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Apply box SA = 2(lw + lh + wh) = 2((8)(4) + (8)(2) + (4)(2)) = 2(32 + 16 + 8) = 2(56) = 112 in². (56 forgets to multiply by 2; 64 is the volume 8 × 4 × 2.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Surface area of a box doubles the sum of the three distinct face areas: 2(lw + lh + wh).","steps":["Face areas: lw = (8)(4) = 32, lh = (8)(2) = 16, wh = (4)(2) = 8.","Add them: 32 + 16 + 8 = 56.","Double: 2 × 56 = 112 in²."],"whyCorrect":"Counting all six faces directly, two each of 32, 16, and 8, gives 64 + 32 + 16 = 112 in².","distractors":{"1":"100 in² comes from an addition slip inside the parentheses; the three faces sum to 56, not 50.","2":"56 in² is the three distinct faces without doubling for their opposites.","3":"64 in² is the volume 8 × 4 × 2, not the surface area."},"commonMistake":"Computing the volume when the question asks for surface area. Surface area is measured in square units and uses the face areas."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":3,"stem":"A cylinder has a radius of 3 cm and a height of 10 cm. Using π ≈ 3.14, what is its total surface area? (cylinder SA = 2πr² + 2πrh.)","options":["188.4 cm²","273.18 cm²","244.92 cm²","216.66 cm²"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Apply cylinder SA = 2πr² + 2πrh. The two circular ends: 2(3.14)(3²) = 2(3.14)(9) = 56.52 cm². The side (lateral) surface: 2(3.14)(3)(10) = 188.4 cm². Total = 56.52 + 188.4 = 244.92 cm². (188.4 counts only the side; 216.66 forgets one circular end.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"A cylinder's total surface area is two circular ends plus the lateral surface: 2πr² + 2πrh.","steps":["Two ends: 2(3.14)(3²) = 2(3.14)(9) = 56.52 cm².","Side (lateral) surface: 2(3.14)(3)(10) = 188.4 cm².","Total: 56.52 + 188.4 = 244.92 cm²."],"whyCorrect":"Both terms are included exactly once: the pair of ends (56.52) and the wrap-around side (188.4).","distractors":{"0":"188.4 cm² is only the lateral surface, leaving off both circular ends.","1":"273.18 cm² adds πr² = 28.26 one time too many, as if the cylinder had three circular ends.","3":"216.66 cm² includes only one end (188.4 + 28.26) instead of both."},"commonMistake":"Dropping one or both circular ends. A closed cylinder needs the 2πr² term in full."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":3,"stem":"A cylindrical can has a diameter of 10 cm and a height of 4 cm. Using π ≈ 3.14, what is its total surface area? (cylinder SA = 2πr² + 2πrh.)","options":["879.2 cm²","282.6 cm²","408.2 cm²","125.6 cm²"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"First find the radius: r = diameter / 2 = 10 / 2 = 5 cm. Then SA = 2πr² + 2πrh = 2(3.14)(5²) + 2(3.14)(5)(4) = 2(3.14)(25) + 2(3.14)(20) = 157 + 125.6 = 282.6 cm². (879.2 wrongly uses the diameter 10 as the radius; 125.6 counts only the side.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Convert the diameter to a radius before using any cylinder formula.","steps":["Radius: r = 10 ÷ 2 = 5 cm.","Two ends: 2(3.14)(5²) = 2(3.14)(25) = 157 cm².","Side surface: 2(3.14)(5)(4) = 125.6 cm².","Total: 157 + 125.6 = 282.6 cm²."],"whyCorrect":"With r = 5 both terms are consistent, and their sum 157 + 125.6 = 282.6 cm² accounts for the ends and the side exactly once each.","distractors":{"0":"879.2 cm² uses the diameter 10 as the radius in both terms: 2(3.14)(100) + 2(3.14)(10)(4).","2":"408.2 cm² uses the correct radius for the ends but the diameter 10 in the side term (157 + 251.2).","3":"125.6 cm² is only the lateral surface, leaving off both circular ends."},"commonMistake":"Plugging the diameter straight into the formula. Halve it first: r = 10 ÷ 2 = 5."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":1,"stem":"A storage box is 6 cm long, 4 cm wide, and 5 cm tall. What is its volume? (V = L × W × H.)","options":["120 cm³","74 cm³","15 cm³","148 cm³"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Apply V = L × W × H = 6 × 4 × 5 = 120 cm³. (148 is the surface area 2(24 + 30 + 20); 15 is just the sum of the dimensions.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Volume of a rectangular box is length × width × height, in cubic units.","steps":["Multiply the dimensions: 6 × 4 = 24.","Multiply by the height: 24 × 5 = 120 cm³."],"whyCorrect":"Each of the 5 layers holds 6 × 4 = 24 unit cubes, and 5 × 24 = 120.","distractors":{"1":"74 cm³ is the sum of the three distinct face areas (24 + 30 + 20), part of a surface-area calculation.","2":"15 cm³ just adds the dimensions 6 + 4 + 5 instead of multiplying them.","3":"148 cm³ is the surface area 2(24 + 30 + 20), not the volume."},"commonMistake":"Confusing volume with surface area. Volume multiplies all three dimensions and carries cubic units."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"A cylinder has a radius of 2 cm and a height of 7 cm. Using π ≈ 3.14, what is its volume? (V = πr²h.)","options":["43.96 cm³","28 cm³","87.92 cm³","175.84 cm³"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Apply V = πr²h = (3.14)(2²)(7) = (3.14)(4)(7) = (3.14)(28) = 87.92 cm³. (43.96 forgets to square the radius and uses 3.14 × 2 × 7; 28 forgets to multiply by π.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Cylinder volume is πr²h: square the radius before multiplying.","steps":["Square the radius: 2² = 4.","Multiply: (3.14)(4)(7) = (3.14)(28) = 87.92 cm³."],"whyCorrect":"Estimate check: r²h = 28, and 28 × 3.14 is a bit under 90, so 87.92 cm³ is the right size.","distractors":{"0":"43.96 cm³ forgets to square the radius, computing 3.14 × 2 × 7.","1":"28 cm³ is r²h without multiplying by π.","3":"175.84 cm³ doubles the correct volume, as if the formula were 2πr²h."},"commonMistake":"Skipping the square on the radius. In πr²h only the radius is squared, and it must be."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":3,"stem":"A cylindrical tank has a diameter of 6 m and a height of 10 m. Using π ≈ 3.14, what is its volume? (V = πr²h.)","options":["188.4 m³","1130.4 m³","282.6 m³","94.2 m³"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"First find the radius: r = diameter / 2 = 6 / 2 = 3 m. Then V = πr²h = (3.14)(3²)(10) = (3.14)(9)(10) = 282.6 m³. (1130.4 wrongly uses the diameter 6 as the radius; 94.2 forgets to square the radius.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Halve the diameter to get the radius before applying V = πr²h.","steps":["Radius: r = 6 ÷ 2 = 3 m.","Square it: 3² = 9.","Multiply: (3.14)(9)(10) = 282.6 m³."],"whyCorrect":"Estimate check: 9 × 10 = 90, and 90 × 3.14 is just over 280, so 282.6 m³ is consistent.","distractors":{"0":"188.4 m³ computes 3.14 × 6 × 10, using the diameter without ever squaring a radius.","1":"1130.4 m³ uses the diameter 6 as the radius: (3.14)(36)(10).","3":"94.2 m³ forgets to square the radius, computing (3.14)(3)(10)."},"commonMistake":"Treating the diameter as the radius. That single slip inflates the volume by a factor of 4."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"Two triangles are similar. The smaller triangle has sides 3 cm, 4 cm, and 5 cm. The larger triangle is created using a scale factor of 4. What is the perimeter of the larger triangle?","options":["48 cm","12 cm","60 cm","24 cm"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"With a scale factor of 4, each side of the larger triangle is 4 times the matching smaller side: 12 cm, 16 cm, and 20 cm. The perimeter is 12 + 16 + 20 = 48 cm. (You can also find the small perimeter 3 + 4 + 5 = 12 and multiply by 4 to get 48. The answer 12 is only the smaller triangle's perimeter.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Scaling every side by a factor scales the perimeter by the same factor.","steps":["Scale each side by 4: 3 → 12, 4 → 16, 5 → 20.","Add the new sides: 12 + 16 + 20 = 48 cm."],"whyCorrect":"Shortcut check: the small perimeter is 3 + 4 + 5 = 12, and 12 × 4 = 48 cm, matching the side-by-side calculation.","distractors":{"1":"12 cm is the smaller triangle's perimeter, before any scaling.","2":"60 cm comes from scaling by 5 instead of 4, or from adding the original perimeter on top of the scaled one (48 + 12).","3":"24 cm scales the perimeter by 2 instead of 4."},"commonMistake":"Forgetting that perimeter scales linearly with the scale factor. Area would scale by 4² = 16, but perimeter scales by 4."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"On a map, 1 cm represents 15 km. Two cities are 8 cm apart on the map. What is the actual distance between the cities?","options":["120 km","1.875 km","23 km","15 km"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Multiply the map distance by the scale: 8 cm × 15 km per cm = 120 km. (23 km adds 8 and 15; 1.875 km divides instead of multiplying.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"With a map scale, multiply the map distance by the real-world amount each unit represents.","steps":["Each map centimeter stands for 15 km.","Multiply: 8 cm × 15 km per cm = 120 km."],"whyCorrect":"Unit check: cm × (km per cm) leaves km, and 8 fifteens is 120.","distractors":{"1":"1.875 km divides 15 by 8 instead of multiplying the map distance by the scale.","2":"23 km adds 8 and 15, mixing a distance with a rate.","3":"15 km is the real distance for only 1 cm of map, ignoring the other 7 cm."},"commonMistake":"Adding or dividing the two numbers. A scale is a rate, so the map distance must be multiplied by it."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Convert Within and Between Standard and Metric Units","difficulty":1,"stem":"Convert 25°C to degrees Fahrenheit using °F = (9/5)°C + 32.","options":["45°F","57°F","77°F","-3.9°F"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Apply °F = (9/5)°C + 32 = (9/5)(25) + 32 = 45 + 32 = 77°F. (45 forgets to add 32; -3.9 uses the wrong direction formula (5/9)(25 − 32).)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Converting Celsius to Fahrenheit means multiplying by 9/5 first, then adding 32.","steps":["Multiply: (9/5)(25) = 45.","Add 32: 45 + 32 = 77°F."],"whyCorrect":"Reverse check: (5/9)(77 − 32) = (5/9)(45) = 25°C, recovering the original temperature.","distractors":{"0":"45°F is (9/5)(25) without adding the 32.","1":"57°F adds 32 to 25 without first multiplying by 9/5.","3":"−3.9°F applies the reverse formula (5/9)(25 − 32), converting in the wrong direction."},"commonMistake":"Stopping after the multiplication. The +32 shift is part of the formula, not optional."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Convert Within and Between Standard and Metric Units","difficulty":2,"stem":"Convert 50°F to degrees Celsius using °C = (5/9)(°F − 32).","options":["10°C","122°C","27.8°C","18°C"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Apply °C = (5/9)(°F − 32) = (5/9)(50 − 32) = (5/9)(18) = 10°C. (27.8 forgets to subtract 32 first; 122 uses the wrong direction (9/5)(50) + 32; 18 forgets to multiply by 5/9.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"Converting Fahrenheit to Celsius means subtracting 32 first, then multiplying by 5/9.","steps":["Subtract 32: 50 − 32 = 18.","Multiply: (5/9)(18) = 10°C."],"whyCorrect":"Reverse check: (9/5)(10) + 32 = 18 + 32 = 50°F, recovering the original temperature.","distractors":{"1":"122°C applies the reverse formula (9/5)(50) + 32, converting in the wrong direction.","2":"27.8°C multiplies 50 by 5/9 without subtracting 32 first.","3":"18°C stops after 50 − 32, forgetting the 5/9 factor."},"commonMistake":"Multiplying before subtracting. In this direction the −32 must happen inside the parentheses first."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Convert Within and Between Standard and Metric Units","difficulty":1,"stem":"Water boils at 100°C. Convert 100°C to degrees Fahrenheit using °F = (9/5)°C + 32.","options":["212°F","180°F","132°F","37.8°F"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Apply °F = (9/5)°C + 32 = (9/5)(100) + 32 = 180 + 32 = 212°F. (180 forgets to add 32; 37.8 uses the wrong direction (5/9)(100 − 32).)","rationale":{"takeaway":"For Celsius to Fahrenheit, multiply by 9/5 and then add 32.","steps":["Multiply: (9/5)(100) = 180.","Add 32: 180 + 32 = 212°F."],"whyCorrect":"212°F is the known boiling point of water, matching 100°C.","distractors":{"1":"180°F is (9/5)(100) without adding the 32.","2":"132°F adds 32 to 100 without first multiplying by 9/5.","3":"37.8°F applies the reverse formula (5/9)(100 − 32), converting in the wrong direction."},"commonMistake":"Skipping one of the two operations. Both the 9/5 factor and the +32 shift are required."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Convert Within and Between Standard and Metric Units","difficulty":3,"stem":"Normal human body temperature is 98.6°F. Convert this to degrees Celsius using °C = (5/9)(°F − 32).","options":["54.8°C","37°C","66.6°C","209.5°C"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Apply °C = (5/9)(°F − 32) = (5/9)(98.6 − 32) = (5/9)(66.6) = 37°C. (66.6 forgets to multiply by 5/9; 209.5 uses the wrong direction (9/5)(98.6) + 32.)","rationale":{"takeaway":"For Fahrenheit to Celsius, subtract 32 before multiplying by 5/9.","steps":["Subtract 32: 98.6 − 32 = 66.6.","Multiply: (5/9)(66.6) = 37°C."],"whyCorrect":"37°C is the standard value for normal body temperature, and (9/5)(37) + 32 = 98.6°F confirms it.","distractors":{"0":"54.8°C multiplies 98.6 by 5/9 without subtracting 32 first.","2":"66.6°C stops after 98.6 − 32, forgetting the 5/9 factor.","3":"209.5°C applies the reverse formula (9/5)(98.6) + 32, converting in the wrong direction."},"commonMistake":"Applying the operations in the wrong order. The subtraction sits inside the parentheses and must come first."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Percents","difficulty":1,"stem":"15 is 25% of what number?","options":["3.75","75","60","40"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"If 15 is 25% of the whole, then whole = 15 ÷ 0.25 = 60. Check: 25% of 60 = 0.25 × 60 = 15.","rationale":{"takeaway":"When the part and the percent are known, divide the part by the percent as a decimal to find the whole.","steps":["Translate: 15 = 0.25 × whole.","Divide: whole = 15 ÷ 0.25 = 60."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 25% of 60 = 0.25 × 60 = 15, matching the given part.","distractors":{"0":"3.75 takes 25% of 15 (15 × 0.25) instead of dividing by the percent.","1":"75 treats 15 as 20% of the whole (15 ÷ 0.20), as if 25% meant one fifth.","3":"40 adds 15 and 25, combining a value with a percent as if they were like quantities."},"commonMistake":"Multiplying by the percent when the whole is unknown. Multiplying finds a part; dividing recovers the whole."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Percents","difficulty":2,"stem":"A 20% tip on a restaurant bill came to $8. What was the amount of the bill before the tip?","options":["$40","$48","$160","$1.60"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The tip is 20% of the bill, so bill = $8 ÷ 0.20 = $40. Check: 20% of $40 = 0.20 × 40 = $8. The $48 distractor mistakenly adds the tip to the bill.","rationale":{"takeaway":"If a known amount is a percent of an unknown total, divide the amount by the percent as a decimal.","steps":["Translate: 8 = 0.20 × bill.","Divide: bill = 8 ÷ 0.20 = 40."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 20% of $40 = 0.20 × 40 = $8, exactly the tip given.","distractors":{"1":"$48 is the bill plus the tip (40 + 8); the question asks for the bill before the tip.","2":"$160 multiplies 8 by 20 instead of dividing by 0.20.","3":"$1.60 takes 20% of the tip (8 × 0.20) instead of dividing."},"commonMistake":"Treating the tip as a percent of itself. The 20% applies to the unknown bill, so divide the tip by 0.20."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Percents","difficulty":2,"stem":"A student answered 18 questions correctly, which was 75% of the test. How many questions were on the test?","options":["22","93","24","13.5"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"18 is 75% of the total, so total = 18 ÷ 0.75 = 24. Check: 75% of 24 = 0.75 × 24 = 18.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Divide the known part by the percent as a decimal to recover the whole.","steps":["Translate: 18 = 0.75 × total.","Divide: total = 18 ÷ 0.75 = 24."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 75% of 24 = 0.75 × 24 = 18, matching the number answered correctly.","distractors":{"0":"22 comes from adding about 25% of 18 to 18 (18 × 1.25 = 22.5, rounded) instead of dividing by 0.75.","1":"93 adds the numbers 75 and 18 as if a percent and a count could be combined directly.","3":"13.5 multiplies 18 by 0.75, which finds 75% of the part rather than the whole."},"commonMistake":"Multiplying by 0.75 when the total is unknown. The 18 is already the 75% piece, so divide."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Percents","difficulty":3,"stem":"After a 30% discount, a jacket sold for $49. What was the original price?","options":["$63.70","$70","$163.33","$79"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The sale price is 100% − 30% = 70% of the original, so original = $49 ÷ 0.70 = $70. Check: 70% of $70 = 0.70 × 70 = $49. Dividing by 0.30 instead gives the wrong $163.33.","rationale":{"takeaway":"After a discount, the sale price is (100% − discount%) of the original, so divide the sale price by that remaining fraction.","steps":["The sale price represents 100% − 30% = 70% of the original.","Divide: original = 49 ÷ 0.70 = 70."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 30% off $70 removes $21, leaving $49, exactly the sale price.","distractors":{"0":"$63.70 adds 30% of the sale price back (49 × 1.30) instead of dividing by 0.70; the 30% was taken from the original price, not the sale price.","2":"$163.33 divides by the discount rate 0.30 instead of the remaining 0.70.","3":"$79 adds 30 dollars instead of undoing a 30 percent reduction."},"commonMistake":"Reversing a percent discount by adding the same percent back. Percents of different bases are not interchangeable."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":1,"stem":"Simplify the expression: 3(x + 2) − 2x","options":["5x + 6","x + 2","x + 5","x + 6"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Distribute: 3(x + 2) = 3x + 6. Then 3x + 6 − 2x = (3x − 2x) + 6 = x + 6.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Distribute across the parentheses first, then combine like terms.","steps":["Distribute: 3(x + 2) = 3x + 6.","Combine like terms: 3x + 6 − 2x = (3x − 2x) + 6 = x + 6."],"whyCorrect":"Check with x = 1: original 3(1 + 2) − 2 = 9 − 2 = 7, and x + 6 = 7. They match.","distractors":{"0":"5x + 6 adds the 2x instead of subtracting it (3x + 2x).","1":"x + 2 distributes the 3 to x but not to the 2 inside the parentheses.","2":"x + 5 adds 3 + 2 for the constant instead of multiplying 3 × 2."},"commonMistake":"Distributing to only the first term. The 3 must multiply both x and 2."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":2,"stem":"Simplify the expression: 5x − 2(x − 4)","options":["3x − 4","7x − 8","3x − 8","3x + 8"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Distribute −2 across (x − 4): −2x + 8. Then 5x − 2x + 8 = 3x + 8. Forgetting the sign change on −2 × −4 gives the 3x − 8 distractor.","rationale":{"takeaway":"When subtracting a group, distribute the negative to every term inside, flipping each sign.","steps":["Distribute −2 across (x − 4): −2x + 8.","Combine: 5x − 2x + 8 = 3x + 8."],"whyCorrect":"Check with x = 1: original 5 − 2(1 − 4) = 5 − 2(−3) = 5 + 6 = 11, and 3(1) + 8 = 11. They match.","distractors":{"0":"3x − 4 multiplies −2 by x but copies the −4 without multiplying it.","1":"7x − 8 adds 2(x − 4) instead of subtracting it, giving 5x + 2x − 8.","2":"3x − 8 misses the sign change on the last term; −2 × (−4) is +8, not −8."},"commonMistake":"Forgetting that a negative times a negative is positive. The −2 acting on −4 produces +8."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":2,"stem":"Simplify the expression: 4(2x + 3) − 3(x − 1)","options":["5x + 15","5x + 11","5x + 9","11x + 9"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Distribute: 4(2x + 3) = 8x + 12 and −3(x − 1) = −3x + 3. Combine: (8x − 3x) + (12 + 3) = 5x + 15.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Distribute each factor across its own parentheses, watching signs, then combine like terms.","steps":["Distribute: 4(2x + 3) = 8x + 12.","Distribute: −3(x − 1) = −3x + 3.","Combine: (8x − 3x) + (12 + 3) = 5x + 15."],"whyCorrect":"Check with x = 1: original 4(5) − 3(0) = 20, and 5(1) + 15 = 20. They match.","distractors":{"1":"5x + 11 multiplies −3 by x but subtracts 1 instead of computing −3 × (−1) = +3.","2":"5x + 9 makes a sign error on the last term, treating −3(x − 1) as −3x − 3.","3":"11x + 9 adds 3x instead of subtracting it and also carries the −3 sign error."},"commonMistake":"Losing the sign on −3 × (−1). Subtracting a negative inside the distribution adds 3."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":3,"stem":"Simplify the expression: 2(3x − 5) − (4x − 7)","options":["10x − 3","2x − 13","2x − 3","2x − 17"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Distribute: 2(3x − 5) = 6x − 10 and −(4x − 7) = −4x + 7. Combine: (6x − 4x) + (−10 + 7) = 2x − 3. Not distributing the negative to −7 gives the 2x − 17 distractor.","rationale":{"takeaway":"A bare minus in front of parentheses distributes as −1 to every term inside.","steps":["Distribute: 2(3x − 5) = 6x − 10.","Distribute the negative: −(4x − 7) = −4x + 7.","Combine: (6x − 4x) + (−10 + 7) = 2x − 3."],"whyCorrect":"Check with x = 2: original 2(1) − (1) = 1, and 2(2) − 3 = 1. They match.","distractors":{"0":"10x − 3 adds the 4x instead of subtracting it (6x + 4x).","1":"2x − 13 mishandles the constants; distributing the negative gives +7, so they combine as −10 + 7 = −3, not −13.","3":"2x − 17 distributes the negative to 4x but not to −7, computing −10 − 7."},"commonMistake":"Distributing the leading negative to only the first term inside the parentheses. Both 4x and −7 must flip sign."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":1,"stem":"Solve the inequality: x + 5 < 12","options":["x < 7","x < 17","x > 7","x > 17"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Subtract 5 from both sides: x < 12 − 5, so x < 7. No sign flip is needed because we did not multiply or divide by a negative.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Solve simple inequalities like equations; the direction flips only when multiplying or dividing by a negative.","steps":["Subtract 5 from both sides: x < 12 − 5.","Simplify: x < 7."],"whyCorrect":"Check a value: x = 6 gives 6 + 5 = 11 < 12, true; x = 8 gives 13 < 12, false. The boundary 7 is right.","distractors":{"1":"x < 17 adds 5 to 12 instead of subtracting it.","2":"x > 7 flips the inequality even though nothing was multiplied or divided by a negative.","3":"x > 17 makes both errors: adds 5 and flips the direction."},"commonMistake":"Flipping the inequality out of habit. Adding or subtracting never changes the direction."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":2,"stem":"Solve the inequality: −2x + 1 < 7","options":["x > 3","x > −3","x < 3","x < −3"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Subtract 1: −2x < 6. Divide both sides by −2 and flip the sign: x > −3. Forgetting to flip gives the x < −3 distractor.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Dividing an inequality by a negative number reverses its direction.","steps":["Subtract 1 from both sides: −2x < 6.","Divide by −2 and flip the sign: x > −3."],"whyCorrect":"Check x = 0 (which satisfies x > −3): −2(0) + 1 = 1 < 7, true. Check x = −4 (excluded): 8 + 1 = 9 < 7, false.","distractors":{"0":"x > 3 flips correctly but drops the negative sign on the boundary; 6 ÷ (−2) = −3.","2":"x < 3 ignores the negative coefficient entirely, solving 2x + 1 < 7 instead.","3":"x < −3 divides by −2 but forgets to flip the inequality direction."},"commonMistake":"Keeping the inequality direction after dividing by −2. That single flip is the whole point of the rule."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":2,"stem":"Solve the inequality: 3x − 4 ≥ 11","options":["x ≤ 5","x ≥ 21/3","x ≥ 7","x ≥ 5"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Add 4: 3x ≥ 15. Divide by 3 (positive, no flip): x ≥ 5. Check: 3(5) − 4 = 11, which satisfies ≥ 11.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Undo subtraction first, then divide; dividing by a positive number keeps the inequality direction.","steps":["Add 4 to both sides: 3x ≥ 15.","Divide by 3 (positive, so no flip): x ≥ 5."],"whyCorrect":"Check the boundary: 3(5) − 4 = 11, which satisfies ≥ 11, and larger x only increases the left side.","distractors":{"0":"x ≤ 5 flips the direction even though the division was by positive 3.","1":"x ≥ 21/3 simplifies to x ≥ 7, an addition slip (11 + 4 = 15, not 21); it wrongly excludes x = 5, which already satisfies the inequality.","2":"x ≥ 7 uses a boundary that is too high; x = 5 and x = 6 satisfy the original inequality but this answer excludes them."},"commonMistake":"Flipping the sign on every division. Only division or multiplication by a negative reverses an inequality."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":3,"stem":"Solve the inequality: 8 − 3x ≤ 23","options":["x ≥ 5","x ≥ −5","x ≤ −5","x ≤ 5"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Subtract 8: −3x ≤ 15. Divide both sides by −3 and flip the sign: x ≥ −5. Forgetting to flip gives the x ≤ −5 distractor.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Isolate the x-term, and remember the direction flips when dividing by a negative.","steps":["Subtract 8 from both sides: −3x ≤ 15.","Divide by −3 and flip the sign: x ≥ −5."],"whyCorrect":"Check x = 0 (included): 8 − 0 = 8 ≤ 23, true. Check x = −6 (excluded): 8 + 18 = 26 ≤ 23, false.","distractors":{"0":"x ≥ 5 drops the negative on the boundary; 15 ÷ (−3) = −5.","2":"x ≤ −5 divides by −3 but forgets to flip the inequality direction.","3":"x ≤ 5 ignores the negative coefficient, solving 3x ≤ 15 as if the sign were not there."},"commonMistake":"Forgetting the flip when the x-term has a negative coefficient. Dividing by −3 must reverse ≤ to ≥."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":1,"stem":"If you multiply two odd numbers together, the product is always:","options":["Odd","Even","Sometimes odd and sometimes even","Zero"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Odd × odd always gives an odd result. For example, 3 × 5 = 15 and 7 × 9 = 63, both odd. So the product is always odd.","rationale":{"takeaway":"A product is even only when at least one factor is even; two odd factors always give an odd product.","steps":["An even product needs a factor of 2 somewhere.","Odd numbers have no factor of 2, so odd × odd cannot produce one.","Test examples: 3 × 5 = 15 and 7 × 9 = 63, both odd."],"whyCorrect":"Algebra check: (2a + 1)(2b + 1) = 4ab + 2a + 2b + 1, which is one more than an even number, so always odd.","distractors":{"1":"Even would require a factor of 2, and neither odd factor supplies one.","2":"It is never even; every example of odd × odd comes out odd, with no exceptions.","3":"A product is zero only when a factor is zero, and odd numbers are never zero."},"commonMistake":"Assuming multiplication mixes parity the way addition does. For products, one even factor forces even; all odd factors force odd."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":1,"stem":"The sum of an even number and an odd number is always:","options":["A multiple of 4","Odd","Prime","Even"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Even + odd is always odd. For example, 6 + 3 = 9 and 8 + 5 = 13, both odd.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Even plus odd is always odd, because one unit is left unpaired.","steps":["An even number splits into pairs; an odd number splits into pairs with 1 left over.","Adding them still leaves exactly 1 unpaired, so the sum is odd.","Test examples: 6 + 3 = 9 and 8 + 5 = 13, both odd."],"whyCorrect":"Algebra check: 2a + (2b + 1) = 2(a + b) + 1, which is odd by definition.","distractors":{"0":"6 + 3 = 9 is not a multiple of 4, so the sum is not always one.","2":"6 + 9 = 15 is odd but not prime (3 × 5), so prime is not guaranteed.","3":"A sum is even only when both addends are even or both are odd; one of each leaves an odd total."},"commonMistake":"Guessing that sums behave like products. For sums, matching parity gives even; mixed parity gives odd."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which expression produces an odd result?","options":["4 × 7","3 + 5","9 × 3","2 + 6"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"4 × 7 = 28 (even), 3 + 5 = 8 (even), 9 × 3 = 27 (odd), 2 + 6 = 8 (even). Only odd × odd, here 9 × 3, gives an odd result.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Only odd × odd yields an odd result; any even factor or matched-parity sum comes out even.","steps":["4 × 7 = 28, even, because 4 is even.","3 + 5 = 8, even, because odd + odd is even.","9 × 3 = 27, odd, because both factors are odd.","2 + 6 = 8, even, because even + even is even."],"whyCorrect":"9 × 3 = 27 ends in 7, an odd digit, confirming the only odd result among the four.","distractors":{"0":"4 × 7 = 28 is even; the even factor 4 forces an even product.","1":"3 + 5 = 8 is even; two odd numbers sum to an even number.","3":"2 + 6 = 8 is even; two even numbers always sum to an even number."},"commonMistake":"Applying the product rule to sums. Odd + odd gives even, while odd × odd gives odd."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":1,"stem":"What is 4.8 ÷ 0.6?","options":["80","0.8","0.08","8"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Move both decimals one place to get 48 ÷ 6 = 8. So 4.8 ÷ 0.6 = 8.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Shift both decimal points the same number of places to make the divisor a whole number, then divide.","steps":["Move each decimal one place right: 4.8 ÷ 0.6 becomes 48 ÷ 6.","Divide: 48 ÷ 6 = 8."],"whyCorrect":"Check by multiplying back: 8 × 0.6 = 4.8.","distractors":{"0":"80 shifts the dividend an extra place, as if computing 48 ÷ 0.6.","1":"0.8 divides correctly to 8 but then shifts the decimal left for no reason.","2":"0.08 shifts two places in the wrong direction after dividing."},"commonMistake":"Moving the two decimal points unequally. Both numbers must shift the same number of places to keep the quotient unchanged."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"type":"FILL_BLANK","stem":"Calculate: 5.6 ÷ 0.7 = ____","options":[],"correct":["8","8.0"],"explanation":"Move both decimals one place to make a whole-number divisor: 56 ÷ 7 = 8. So 5.6 ÷ 0.7 = 8.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Multiply both numbers by 10 to clear the decimal from the divisor, then divide whole numbers.","steps":["Shift both decimals one place: 5.6 ÷ 0.7 becomes 56 ÷ 7.","Divide: 56 ÷ 7 = 8."],"whyCorrect":"Check by multiplying back: 8 × 0.7 = 5.6.","commonMistake":"Shifting only one of the two decimal points, which changes the value of the quotient by a factor of 10."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"What is 0.144 ÷ 1.2?","options":["12","0.12","1.2","0.012"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Move each decimal one place: 1.44 ÷ 12 = 0.12. So 0.144 ÷ 1.2 = 0.12.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Shift both decimals equally to make the divisor whole, then place the decimal carefully in the quotient.","steps":["Move each decimal one place right: 0.144 ÷ 1.2 becomes 1.44 ÷ 12.","Divide: 1.44 ÷ 12 = 0.12."],"whyCorrect":"Check by multiplying back: 0.12 × 1.2 = 0.144.","distractors":{"0":"12 drops the decimal entirely, as if computing 144 ÷ 12.","2":"1.2 places the decimal one spot too far right, ten times too large.","3":"0.012 places the decimal one spot too far left, ten times too small."},"commonMistake":"Losing track of the decimal after dividing. Estimate first: 0.144 is a bit more than a tenth of 1.2, so the answer must be near 0.1."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":1,"stem":"What value of n makes the equation 3/4 = n/20 true?","options":["16","15","9","12"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Since 4 × 5 = 20, multiply the numerator by 5 as well: 3 × 5 = 15. So 3/4 = 15/20 and n = 15.","rationale":{"takeaway":"To build an equivalent fraction, multiply the numerator and denominator by the same factor.","steps":["Find the factor that turns 4 into 20: 20 ÷ 4 = 5.","Multiply the numerator by the same 5: 3 × 5 = 15."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 15/20 reduces by 5 back to 3/4, so the fractions are equal.","distractors":{"0":"16 comes from subtracting 4 from 20 instead of scaling; 16/20 reduces to 4/5, not 3/4.","2":"9 multiplies the numerator by itself (3 × 3) instead of by the scale factor 5.","3":"12 multiplies the numerator by the denominator (3 × 4); 12/20 reduces to 3/5, not 3/4."},"commonMistake":"Using addition or the wrong multiplier. Whatever multiplies the denominator must multiply the numerator identically."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"What is the least common denominator of 1/6 and 3/8?","options":["48","14","24","12"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The multiples of 6 are 6, 12, 18, 24 and of 8 are 8, 16, 24. The smallest shared multiple is 24.","rationale":{"takeaway":"The least common denominator is the smallest number that both denominators divide evenly.","steps":["List multiples of 6: 6, 12, 18, 24, ...","List multiples of 8: 8, 16, 24, ...","The first shared multiple is 24."],"whyCorrect":"24 ÷ 6 = 4 and 24 ÷ 8 = 3, both whole numbers, and no smaller number works for both.","distractors":{"0":"48 is a common multiple (6 × 8) but not the least one; 24 is smaller and works.","1":"14 is the sum 6 + 8; it is not a multiple of either denominator.","3":"12 is a multiple of 6 but not of 8 (12 ÷ 8 is not whole)."},"commonMistake":"Multiplying the denominators automatically. That always gives a common denominator, but not necessarily the least one."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"Express 2/5 as an equivalent fraction with a denominator of 35.","options":["12/35","14/35","7/35","10/35"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Since 5 × 7 = 35, multiply the numerator by 7: 2 × 7 = 14. So 2/5 = 14/35.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Scale the numerator by the same factor used on the denominator.","steps":["Find the factor: 35 ÷ 5 = 7.","Multiply the numerator: 2 × 7 = 14, giving 14/35."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 14/35 reduces by 7 back to 2/5.","distractors":{"0":"12/35 multiplies the numerator by 6 instead of the correct factor 7.","2":"7/35 puts the scale factor itself in the numerator; 7/35 reduces to 1/5, not 2/5.","3":"10/35 multiplies the numerator by the original denominator 5; 10/35 reduces to 2/7, not 2/5."},"commonMistake":"Finding the right scale factor but applying it to the wrong number, or not applying it to the numerator at all."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":1,"stem":"Reduce 18/24 to lowest terms.","options":["6/8","3/4","2/3","9/12"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The greatest common factor of 18 and 24 is 6. Dividing both by 6 gives 18/24 = 3/4.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Reduce a fraction by dividing the numerator and denominator by their greatest common factor.","steps":["Find the GCF of 18 and 24: both divide by 6.","Divide: 18 ÷ 6 = 3 and 24 ÷ 6 = 4, giving 3/4."],"whyCorrect":"3 and 4 share no common factor besides 1, so 3/4 is fully reduced, and 3/4 = 18/24 since 3 × 6 = 18 and 4 × 6 = 24.","distractors":{"0":"6/8 divides by 3 only; it is equivalent but still reducible by 2.","2":"2/3 is not equivalent; 2/3 = 16/24, not 18/24.","3":"9/12 divides by 2 only; it is equivalent but still reducible by 3."},"commonMistake":"Stopping after dividing by a small common factor. Lowest terms requires dividing by the greatest common factor."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"Write 24/36 in simplest form.","options":["3/4","4/6","2/3","12/18"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The greatest common factor of 24 and 36 is 12. Dividing both by 12 gives 24/36 = 2/3.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Divide the numerator and denominator by their greatest common factor to reach simplest form.","steps":["Find the GCF of 24 and 36: both divide by 12.","Divide: 24 ÷ 12 = 2 and 36 ÷ 12 = 3, giving 2/3."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 2/3 of 36 is 24, and 2 and 3 share no common factor, so the fraction is fully reduced.","distractors":{"0":"3/4 is not equivalent; 3/4 of 36 is 27, not 24.","1":"4/6 divides by 6 only; it still reduces by 2 to 2/3.","3":"12/18 divides by 2 only; it still reduces by 6."},"commonMistake":"Reducing partway and stopping. Keep dividing until the numerator and denominator share no factor but 1."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"Simplify 16/40 to lowest terms.","options":["2/5","4/10","1/3","8/20"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The greatest common factor of 16 and 40 is 8. Dividing both by 8 gives 16/40 = 2/5.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Divide by the greatest common factor in one step to reach lowest terms.","steps":["Find the GCF of 16 and 40: both divide by 8.","Divide: 16 ÷ 8 = 2 and 40 ÷ 8 = 5, giving 2/5."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 2/5 of 40 is 16, and 2 and 5 share no common factor, so 2/5 is fully reduced.","distractors":{"1":"4/10 divides by 4 only; it still reduces by 2 to 2/5.","2":"1/3 is not equivalent; 16/40 = 0.4 while 1/3 is about 0.33.","3":"8/20 divides by 2 only; it still reduces by 4."},"commonMistake":"Dividing by 2 once or twice and stopping short of the full common factor 8."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":1,"stem":"Convert the mixed number 3 2/5 to an improper fraction.","options":["13/5","17/5","17/3","11/5"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Multiply the whole number by the denominator and add the numerator: 3 × 5 + 2 = 17. Keep the denominator: 17/5.","rationale":{"takeaway":"For a mixed number, multiply the whole number by the denominator, add the numerator, and keep the denominator.","steps":["Multiply: 3 × 5 = 15.","Add the numerator: 15 + 2 = 17.","Keep the denominator: 17/5."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 17 ÷ 5 = 3 remainder 2, which rebuilds 3 2/5.","distractors":{"0":"13/5 subtracts the numerator instead of adding it (3 × 5 − 2).","2":"17/3 gets the numerator right but swaps in the whole number 3 as the denominator; the denominator stays 5.","3":"11/5 multiplies the whole number by itself (3 × 3 + 2) instead of by the denominator 5."},"commonMistake":"Mixing up which numbers multiply and which add. The whole number times the denominator comes first, then add the numerator."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"Write the improper fraction 23/4 as a mixed number.","options":["6 3/4","5 3/4","4 3/4","5 1/4"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Divide 23 by 4 to get 5 with a remainder of 3. So 23/4 = 5 3/4.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Divide the numerator by the denominator; the quotient is the whole number and the remainder stays over the denominator.","steps":["Divide: 23 ÷ 4 = 5 with remainder 3, since 4 × 5 = 20 and 23 − 20 = 3.","Write it as 5 3/4."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 5 × 4 + 3 = 23, rebuilding the original numerator.","distractors":{"0":"6 3/4 rounds the quotient up to 6, but 4 × 6 = 24 already exceeds 23.","2":"4 3/4 undershoots the whole number; 4 × 4 + 3 = 19, not 23.","3":"5 1/4 has the right whole number but the wrong remainder; 23 − 20 = 3, not 1."},"commonMistake":"Losing the remainder during the division. The remainder, not the quotient, becomes the new numerator."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":1,"type":"FILL_BLANK","stem":"Convert the mixed number 4 1/3 to an improper fraction: ____","options":[],"correct":["13/3"],"explanation":"Multiply the whole number by the denominator and add the numerator: 4 × 3 + 1 = 13. Keep the denominator: 13/3.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Multiply the whole number by the denominator, add the numerator, and keep the same denominator.","steps":["Multiply: 4 × 3 = 12.","Add the numerator: 12 + 1 = 13.","Keep the denominator: 13/3."],"whyCorrect":"Check: 13 ÷ 3 = 4 remainder 1, which rebuilds 4 1/3.","commonMistake":"Adding before multiplying or changing the denominator. The denominator never changes in this conversion."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"What is 2/3 × 3/4 in simplest form?","options":["5/12","6/7","1/2","3/8"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Multiply numerators and denominators: (2 × 3)/(3 × 4) = 6/12, which reduces to 1/2.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Multiply fractions straight across: numerator times numerator, denominator times denominator, then reduce.","steps":["Multiply across: (2 × 3)/(3 × 4) = 6/12.","Reduce by 6: 6/12 = 1/2."],"whyCorrect":"Sense check: taking 2/3 of 3/4 should give a bit less than 3/4, and 1/2 fits; also 1/2 of 12 is 6, matching 6/12.","distractors":{"0":"5/12 adds the numerators (2 + 3) while multiplying the denominators, mixing the addition and multiplication rules.","1":"6/7 multiplies the numerators but adds the denominators (3 + 4), another rule mix-up.","3":"3/8 halves 3/4 (divides by 2) instead of multiplying by the full fraction 2/3."},"commonMistake":"Borrowing steps from fraction addition. Multiplication never needs a common denominator; just multiply straight across."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"What is 3/4 ÷ 1/2?","options":["3/8","1 1/2","1 1/4","2/3"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Dividing means multiplying by the reciprocal: 3/4 × 2/1 = 6/4 = 3/2 = 1 1/2.","rationale":{"takeaway":"To divide by a fraction, multiply by its reciprocal.","steps":["Flip the divisor: 3/4 ÷ 1/2 becomes 3/4 × 2/1.","Multiply: 6/4 = 3/2.","Convert: 3/2 = 1 1/2."],"whyCorrect":"Sense check: dividing by one half asks how many halves fit in 3/4, and one and a half halves fit; also 1 1/2 × 1/2 = 3/4.","distractors":{"0":"3/8 multiplies by 1/2 instead of by its reciprocal 2/1.","2":"1 1/4 adds the fractions (3/4 + 1/2 = 5/4) instead of dividing.","3":"2/3 flips the wrong fraction, computing 1/2 ÷ 3/4; division order matters."},"commonMistake":"Forgetting to flip the second fraction, or flipping the first one instead. Only the divisor gets inverted."}},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":3,"stem":"What is 2 1/2 × 1 1/3?","options":["2 1/6","3 2/5","3 1/3","3 1/6"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Convert to improper fractions: 5/2 × 4/3 = 20/6 = 10/3 = 3 1/3.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Convert mixed numbers to improper fractions before multiplying; never multiply the whole and fraction parts separately.","steps":["Convert: 2 1/2 = 5/2 and 1 1/3 = 4/3.","Multiply across: (5 × 4)/(2 × 3) = 20/6.","Simplify: 20/6 = 10/3 = 3 1/3."],"whyCorrect":"Estimate check: 2 1/2 × 1 1/3 should be a bit more than 2 1/2 × 1 = 2 1/2, and 3 1/3 is reasonable; exactly, 10/3 × 3 = 10 = 5/2 × 4.","distractors":{"0":"2 1/6 multiplies the whole numbers (2 × 1) and the fractions (1/2 × 1/3) separately, dropping the cross terms.","1":"3 2/5 mis-simplifies 20/6; the remainder is 2 out of 6, which reduces to 1/3, not 2/5.","3":"3 1/6 is close but comes from mishandling 20/6; 20 ÷ 6 = 3 remainder 2, and 2/6 = 1/3, not 1/6."},"commonMistake":"Multiplying whole parts and fraction parts independently. That skips the cross products and undershoots the answer."}},
];
